{This is one of the typical structures for the variation. Due to the g2-bishop,
Black cannot easily advance his queenside majority. On the other hand, White's
central pawns are mobile. White's plan is simple. After installing the knight
on c5, he will start advancing the central pawns ("f" and "e"). This structure
is particularly favourable for White when the queens are on the board. The
reason is that the advance of the central pawns will weaken Black's king (due
to the pawn contacts e2-e4-e5-e6 or f2-f4-f5-f6). As GM Iossif Dorfman often
says, when we have mobile pawns in the centre, the opponent's king is
potentially weak. In this position, White should play} 1. Na4 {[%cal Ga4c5,
Ge2e4,Gf2f4,Ge4e5] followed by the ideas mentioned in the previous comment.} *

