{Very often, Black puts his bishop on d5 in order to neutralize the pressure
along the long diagonal. In this case, the ideas based on the immediate Nc5
are not that effective. On the other hand, by putting his bishop on d5, Black
does not have good control of the important d4-square. Therefore, in such
positions, White should play} 1. Qc2 {Preparing the thematic d2-d4. After the
exchange of the central pawns, we reach the structure which was discussed in
the explanation of "Typical Position 1". A possible follow-up would be} O-O 2.
d4 exd4 3. Nxd4 Nxd4 4. Bxd4 c6 5. Rfd1 {[%cal Ge4c5,Ge2e4] when White is
ready to follow with Nc5 and e2-e4. White's advantage is obvious.} *

