{Another case when White should opt for d2-d4 is the positions in which Black
wants to exchange the light-squared bishops via h3. For example, we shall take
a look at the diagram. After exchanging the bishops, Black is ready to gain
space in the centre by means of ...f6-f5 followed by ...e5-e4. Therefore, in
this position, White should follow with} 1. d4 $1 Bxg2 2. Kxg2 exd4 3. Rfd1 Qe6
4. Bxd4 $1 {[%csl Gb7,Ge6][%cal Gd4c5,Ge7c5,Ge4c5,Gc5e6,Gc5b7,Gc1c7] We have
reached the structure which was discussed in "Typical Position 1". Black's ...
f7-f6 has weakened the light squares around the king. White would be happy to
install a knight on c5 after exchanging the dark-bishops with Bc5. In such a
case, Black will have difficulties to deal with the threats against the king
combined with the queenside pressure.} *

