{Another common situation arises when White has a pawn on d2 while Black has
good control of the d4-square. In this case, White should think twice before
playing Nc5. Black can answer this move by taking the knight followed by ...
e5-e4. Therefore, White should prepare d2-d4 by means of} 1. Rfd1 $1 {[%cal
Gd2d4] After the exchange of the central pawns, we reach the typical pawn
structure we are already familiar with. Black's best reaction would be} Qc8 {
preparing to answer} 2. d4 {with} f5 3. Nc5 e4 {Black managed to neutralize
the g2-bishop at the price of the bishop pair. White should just follow with}
4. Nxe6 Qxe6 5. Ne5 Nxe5 6. dxe5 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gg2f1] Later on, he can consider
playing e2-e3 followed by Bf1, thus activating the light-squared bishop. In
the long-term, the bishop pair would give White a lasting edge.} *

