{This typical structure very often occurs in the line 1.c4 e5 2.g3 Nc6 3.Nc3
Bc5. White has a space advantage and should keep the tension in the centre
until the moment when his development is enough to develop an the initiative.
Additionally, in positions with a space advantage, we should avoid exchanges.
In such structures, Black tries to provoke the advance d4-d5 which releases
the tension in the centre and closes the g2-bishop. In such a case, Black can
consider playing on the kingside by means of the advance ...f7-f5. In this
line of thoughts, a typical idea for Black would be ...Bg4, planning to
exchange the f3-knight, thus increasing the pressure against the d4-pawn.
Therefore, White should start with} 1. h3 $1 {[%cal Gb2b3,Gd4e5,Gd6e5,Gc1a3]
Preventing the idea ...Bg4. Having space problems, at some point, Black could
run out of useful moves and release the tension in the tension with ...exd4
which grants White stable central domination. White usually releases the
tension in the centre by means of dxe5. This move, however, usually comes
after the prior b2-b3 which allows the gain of a tempo with Ba3. In the
arising symmetrical structure, White is better due to the activity of his
minor pieces, the pressure along the h1-a8 diagonal, and the control of the
important d5-square.} *

