{[%csl Gd5,Re3,Rf5,Rg6,Rh7][%cal Gd1d2,Ga1d1,Ga2a3,Gb3b4,Gc4c5,Gg3g4,Gf3h4,
Gh4f5,Gg2e4,Gb6e3] This is one of typical positions that might arise after
White's dxe5. White should try to achieve such kind of position. His minor
pieces are more active. The g2-bishop creates a latent pressure against
Black's queenside while the d5-knight is a monster. White also enjoys a
considerable space advantage on the queenside. I would suggest the following
plan: 1) By using the d5-knight as shelter, White shall double the rooks on
the d-file 2) We can also consider gaining space on the queenside by means of
a2-a3 followed by b3-b4 and c4-c5 3) Another idea is to make use of the weak
light squares on the kingside by playing g3-g4 followed by Nh4-f5. Meanwhile,
Black does not have counterplay.}  *

