{[%csl Rc7][%cal Gc1b2,Ga1c1,Gc3d5,Gf6d5,Gc4d5,Gc1c7] Another typical
structure arises when in response to dxe5, Black recaptures with a knight. In
this structure, the c4-pawn gives White a stable space advantage. The most
important positional factor is the outpost on d5. White's play is simple. In
the next moves, he will follow with Bb2, Rc1 and Nd5. Of course, Black cannot
live with the d5-knight forever. If he exchanges it, White will recapture with
the c-pawn. Afterwards, by using the semi-open c-file, he can put a huge
pressure against the c7-pawn. If Black decides to chase the d5-knight away
with ...c7-c6, then he will have problems with the d6-pawn. These
considerations justify the opinion of Dorfman who affirms that when we have an
outpost, the opponent will be forced to accept a backward pawn in his camp.}  *

