{[%csl Gb2,Rc8,Gd4][%cal Gc3b5,Gb5d4,Ga2a4] This structure often arises in the
system 1.c4 e5 2.g3 Nf6 3.Bg2 c6. Despite the fact that the position is
symmetrical there factors that give White an advantage: 1) The c8-bishop does
not have a good square 2) The b2-bishop puts pressure on the diagonal a1-h8 3)
White can make use of the important d4-square by means of the manoeuvre Nb5-d4
After putting his knight on d4, White can even consider gaining space on the
kingside. Black's play in such positions is by no means simple.}  *

