{This is the starting position of our line. White delays the move Nc3 and here.
We can see now the main idea of White's move order.} 7. d4 $1 {White strikes
in the centre. Black has two options: To exchange on d4 and to play a passive
position or to push 7...e4.} e4 (7... exd4 $6 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nf6 10. Qa4+
{White plans to develop quickly his pieces using Rd1, Nc3, Be3, Rac1. In the
meantime is not so clear how Black can protect his queenside. This is the
dream "Catalan" position for White.}) 8. Ne5 f5 $1 {The only move to protect
the "f5" pawn/} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Qc2 {White's position is undoubtedly better.
Black's doubled pawns are long-term weaknesses. White's plan is to put
pressure on them and to open the centre with f2-f3 in an appropriate moment.} *

