1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O Be7 {By making
this natural developing move, Black accepts the following damage to his pawn
structure.} ({The careless} 6... Bc5 $2 {runs into} 7. Nxe5 $1 ({Instead,} 7.
Nc3 $6 O-O {tranposes to a fahsionable theoretical line of the English Opening.
}) 7... Bxf2+ 8. Rxf2 Nxe5 9. Nc3 $16 {, with a huge positional advantage.}) ({
The main alternative} 6... Nb6 {is covered in the next chapter. 1-0 (53)
Caruana,F (2812)-Sevian,S (2654) Douglas 2019}) 7. d4 {That's the point! White
takes the opportunity to place his knight in the centre.} (7. Nc3 Nb6 {takes
us to the tabiya.}) 7... e4 {This is practically forced.} (7... exd4 $6 {
is a serious positional concession, since the Bg2 is getting very powerful:} 8.
Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Nf6 10. Qa4+ c6 (10... Bd7 11. Qb3 Rb8 12. Be3 b6 13. Nc3 $16
) 11. Rd1 Qb6 12. Be3 Bc5 (12... Qxb2 $2 13. Bxc6+ $1 Kf8 14. Bf3 $18) 13. Bxc5
Qxc5 14. Nc3 O-O 15. Rac1 Qb6 16. Qc2 Be6 17. Na4 $14 {The knight soon reached
c5, so Black got under strong positional pressure. Badea,B - Popescu,C
Bucharest 1995}) 8. Ne5 f5 {This is the best Black can do, secure the pawn on
e4, so White's light-squared bishop remains out of play for a while.} (8... Bf5
$2 {just drops a pawn:} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. Nd2 Nf6 11. Qc2 $18) ({The same with} 
8... Nxe5 $2 9. dxe5 Bf5 10. Qa4+ Qd7 11. Qxd7+ Kxd7 12. Nd2 $18) 9. Nxc6 bxc6
10. Qc2 {So, the doubled pawns are under pressure from now on. Any way of
defending them looks somewhat uncomfortable.} Qd7 {This somewhat artificial
move is the most common.} ({Black has a wide choice of alternatives:} 10... Bd7
11. Nc3 O-O $146 {This most natural move is a novelty.} ({The previously played
} 11... Bf6 {Buechmann,O - Heck,N Dresden 2014 can be simply met by} 12. e3 O-O
13. Bd2 Rb8 14. a3 $14) 12. f3 {White is glad to liberate his bishop, even
though it somewhat damages his pawn structure.} exf3 13. Rxf3 Bf6 (13... Bd6
14. Rf1 Be6 15. Nxd5 cxd5 16. Bf4 $14) 14. e3 Rb8 15. Rf2 $14) (10... Qd6 {
Black keeps the Bc8 unlocked, but his queen may be attacked soon.} 11. Nc3 Be6
12. Nxd5 Bxd5 ({Worse is} 12... cxd5 $6 13. Bf4 Qb6 14. e3 $16) 13. Bf4 Qd7 14.
f3 exf3 15. Bxf3 O-O {We have been following the game Miroshnichenko, E -
Eljanov, P Kiev 2011 Now White could have increased the pressure with} (15...
Bxf3 16. Rxf3 Qxd4+ 17. Kg2 O-O 18. Rd1 Qf6 19. Bxc7 Rac8 20. Bf4 (20. Ba5))
16. Rac1 {, inviting Black to grab the central pawn:} Bxf3 17. exf3 Qxd4+ 18.
Kg2 Bd6 19. Rfd1 Qf6 20. Bxd6 cxd6 21. Qxc6 Qxb2+ 22. Rc2 Qb6 23. Rxd6 $14 {
Despite major simplifications, White retains an advantage due to the activity
of all his pieces.}) (10... Nb4 {The main idea behind this ambitious move is
to interrupt White's natural development and attack the pawn on d4.} 11. Qa4
Bd7 12. Nc3 O-O ({Black might get rid of one weak pawn with} 12... c5 13. Qd1
cxd4 {, but then the poor location of the Nb4 starts to tell:} 14. Qxd4 O-O ({
The ''greedy''} 14... Nc2 $2 {offers White a crushing attack:} 15. Qxg7 Bf6 16.
Qh6 Nxa1 17. Nd5 Kf7 18. Bf4 $18) 15. Qc4+ Kh8 16. Bf4 $16 {White had a big
positional advantage in Romanov,E - Kunin,V Marrakesh 2010}) 13. a3 $146 {
This novelty is a clear improvement} ({over} 13. Bg5 Bxg5 14. Qxb4 Qe7 15. Qc4+
Qe6 {Black was OK in Ivanchuk,V - Shirov,A Warsaw 2010.}) 13... Nd5 14. Qc4 Kh8
15. Nxd5 Be6 (15... cxd5 16. Qxd5 Rb8 17. b4 Bb5 18. Qa2 Qxd4 19. Be3 Qc4 20.
Rfc1) 16. Qxc6 Bxd5 17. Qc2 Bd6 18. f3 $14 {Black doesn't have sufficient
compensation for the pawn - White will liberate his Bg2 soon.}) ({Dubious is} 
10... O-O $6 11. Qxc6 {Black hardly has anything attractive here. As practice
proves, White is able to consolidate and maintain his extra pawn:} Rb8 12. Nc3
Nb4 ({Equally bad is} 12... Nb6 13. Bf4 Bd6 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Qb5 Be6 16. Qa5 {
Pechac,J - Haring, V Slovakia 2017}) 13. Qc4+ Kh8 14. Bf4 Bd6 15. Bxd6 cxd6 16.
a3 $16 {Gurevich, D - Delanoy,A Geneve 2001}) 11. Nc3 O-O 12. f3 ({In my
opinion, less promising is} 12. Nxd5 cxd5 13. Bf4 c6 14. Rfc1 Bb7 15. e3 {
, as in Topalov,V - Karjakin, S Paris 2017, in view of} g5 $1 $146 16. Be5 Bf6
{, and the ...f5-f4 break seems to offer Black decent counterplay.}) 12... exf3
13. Bxf3 {The light-squared bishop is back in action!} Bf6 14. Rd1 Kh8 {
This position occurred in Sigurdsson, J - Thurrott, A email 2012. Here White
could have converted his superior pawn structure into pressure along the
c-file with} 15. Nxd5 $5 $146 cxd5 16. Bf4 c6 17. Rac1 Bb7 18. h4 Rae8 19. e3
$14 {Black lacks any adequate counterplay, whereas the pawn on c3 is very weak.
} *

