{This is one of the most important positions from the database. White played
the tricky move order (without Nc3) This way we avoid several unpleasant
variations like the lines with Bc5. The other idea of delaying Nc3 is that
White can play b3 followed by Bb2 and d4.} 7. b3 $1 {In the following chapter
you will find analyzed the position after 7...Bd6.} Bd6 $5 {The bishop is not
very well placed here. It is quite easy for White to exchange it and to reach
a position with bishop pair.} 8. Bb2 O-O ({and if} 8... Qe7 9. d4 $1 e4 10.
Nfd2 f5 11. Nc4 {White exchanges the bishop on d6 with slightly better position
}) 9. Nc3 Re8 10. Ne4 Bf8 11. Rc1 $14 {White starts typical play for this line.
The knight will go to c5 putting some pressure on the queenside. The other
idea is to play Nh4 followed by f2-f4 in an appropriate moment.} *

