{[%evp 0,33,16,-12,-1,-36,-42,-51,-22,-27,-42,-25,-44,-27,-6,-15,10,6,19,17,25,
9,22,5,13,4,7,7,-2,-1,10,1,1,-14,-14,-9]} 1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5
Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O Nb6 {This early retreat is aimed at neutralizing the
thematic d2-d4. It isn't really a concession, since after 7.Nc3 Be7 we reach
the main theoretical line.} 7. b3 {A flexible way of handling the position.
White goes for the second fianchetto, while his queen's knight can be
harmoniously placed on d2.} Bd6 {By choosing this spot for the dark-squared
bishop, Black saves a tempo, since the e5-pawn is covered now. On the other
hand, it reduces Black's control of d4 and invites White's knight to attack
the bishop at some point.} 8. Bb2 O-O (8... Qe7 {hardly has an independent
value since Black has to castle soon anyway. Moreover, it yields White an
additional attractive possibility:} 9. d4 $5 e4 (9... O-O 10. dxe5 Nxe5 11. Nc3
c6 {was seen in Ueksti,E - Rodin,E email 2004. Now White could have put Black
in a passive situation by keeping the knights on the board:} 12. Nd4 $1 $146
Rd8 13. Qc2 Bc5 14. Nf5 $14) 10. Nfd2 f5 ({Worse is} 10... e3 $6 11. Nc4 exf2+
12. Rxf2 O-O 13. Nc3 $16 {, with e2-e4 to follow. Black's position is very
cramped.}) 11. Nc4 O-O 12. Nxd6 Qxd6 ({After} 12... cxd6 13. d5 Ne5 14. Nc3 $16
{White has an undeniable positional advantage due to his strong unopposed
dark-squared bishop.}) 13. Ba3 Nb4 14. Nc3 {The pin is quite annoying, even
though Black doesn't lose material.} a5 15. f3 exf3 16. Rxf3 c6 17. Qd2 {
The bishop pair and the potential e2-e4 advance make White's position very
appealing.}) 9. Nc3 {The knight can head to either b5 or e4 to exchange the
important Bd6. As always, White keeps d2-d4 as an option.} Re8 {The most
common. Now, f8 is vacant for the bishop's retreat.} (9... Bg4 {is
traditionally met by} 10. d4 $1 Bxf3 11. Bxf3 exd4 12. Ne4 $1 $146 ({The
previously played} 12. Nb5 Be5 {left the Nb5 misplaced in Hertneck,G - Timman,
J Germany 2001.}) 12... Re8 13. Rc1 Bf8 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Re6 16. Qc1 $36 {
The massive pressure along the c-file and the powerful bishops offer White
more than sufficient compensation for the pawn.}) ({The aggressive} 9... f5 {
weakens the long diagonal and might backfire. For instance,} 10. Nb5 $1 Be6 (
10... e4 11. Nfd4 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 c6 13. d3 $14 {Kerr, S - Busemann, S email 2006
}) 11. Rc1 Qe7 {This position was reached in Karthikeyan, P - Deshpande, A
Taleigao 2019. Now my new natural idea is} 12. d3 $146 Rad8 13. Nxd6 cxd6 14.
e3 Nd5 15. Qd2 $14 {White's chances are preferable due to his bishop pair and
more flexible pawn structure.}) (9... Qe7 10. Nb5 f5 ({Hardly better is} 10...
Be6 11. Nxd6 cxd6 12. e4 f5 {Kerr,S - Kalchev,J email 2007 At this point it
made sense to open up the position with} 13. exf5 $1 $146 Bxf5 14. d4 e4 15.
Nh4 d5 (15... Bd7 16. d5 $36) 16. a4 Qf6 17. Nxf5 Qxf5 18. f3 $16) 11. Nxd6
cxd6 12. d3 f4 13. Qd2 Bg4 14. d4 $1 Rad8 15. Rad1 Nd5 (15... e4 16. d5 exf3
17. exf3 $16) 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Qc1 e4 18. Nd4 $14 {Black's activity on the
kingside came to an end, while White's bishops are extremely powerful. Franke,
H - Antonenko,V email 2014}) 10. Ne4 Bf8 ({I've also examined} 10... Bf5 $146
11. Nxd6 Qxd6 ({After} 11... cxd6 12. Nh4 $1 Be6 13. d4 $36 {The strong
unopposed Bb2 causes Black certain problems.}) 12. d3 a5 13. a3 f6 14. Nd2 $14
{The knight's transfer to c5 offers White the better chances.}) ({Ineffective
is also} 10... Bg4 $146 11. Rc1 a5 (11... Qd7 12. d4 $36) 12. h3 Bh5 13. Nc5
Bxc5 14. Rxc5 f6 15. Nh4 $14) 11. Rc1 f6 {Natural play from both sides led to
this position in Caruana, F - Aronian, L Douglas 2019 Now I find the following
plan quite attractive:} ({In case of} 11... f5 {I like the unexpected} 12. Nc3
$5 e4 (12... Be6 {runs into} 13. e4 $1 f4 14. d4 exd4 15. Ne2 fxg3 16. hxg3 d3
17. Nf4 $36 {White has the superior coordination between the pieces, and the
d3-pawn is going to fall soon.}) 13. Ne1 Be6 14. d3 $14) ({Another popular
continuation is} 11... Bg4 12. h3 Bh5 13. d3 $1 {A decent prophylactic move.} (
{Premature is} 13. Nc5 e4 14. Ne1 Nd4 $132) 13... Nd7 ({In case of} 13... Nd4
14. Nxd4 exd4 15. g4 Bg6 16. Nc5 {The d4-pawn is the main cause of worries.
For instance,} Bxc5 17. Rxc5 c6 18. Qd2 Qe7 19. Rc2 Rad8 20. Qf4 $14 {White
was clearly better in Topalov,V - Vachier Lagrave,M Paris 2017}) ({Too passive
seems also} 13... f6 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 Qd6 16. Qc1 $14 {Tregubov,P -
Fressinet,L Caleta 2016}) 14. Qc2 Rc8 {This was Kosten, A - Ferguson, M
England 1998. Now White should have continued:} 15. a3 $146 a5 (15... Bxf3 16.
Bxf3 Nd4 17. Bxd4 exd4 18. b4 $14) 16. e3 f6 17. Rfd1 $14 {with d3-d4 to
follow.}) 12. Nh4 $5 $146 {A multi-purpose move: White unlocks his powerful
Bg2 and aims to develop an initiative with f2-f4.} Bg4 ({The attempt to
develop counterplay with} 12... a5 {takes a long time, so after} 13. Nc5 Bxc5
14. Rxc5 {White is firmly in a control. For instance,} a4 ({After} 14... Be6
15. Rxc6 bxc6 16. Bxc6 a4 17. Qc2 axb3 18. axb3 {Black doesn't acquire full
compensation.}) 15. Be4 $1 {This offers White control over the b1-h7 diagonal.}
axb3 16. axb3 Bh3 17. Re1 ({Deserving of serious attention is also} 17. Qc2 $5
Bxf1 18. Bxh7+ Kh8 19. Kxf1 {Black's king is very exposed.}) 17... Nd7 18. Rb5
Rb8 19. Qc2 $14 {Black is doomed to passive defence.}) 13. h3 Be6 ({After} 
13... Bh5 14. Nc5 Bxc5 15. Rxc5 {The Bh5 suddenly turns out misplaced, as
illustrated in the following line:} Qd7 16. d4 $1 Rad8 17. Qc1 Bxe2 18. d5 {
Black is very close to a collapse.}) 14. f4 exf4 15. Rxf4 Qd7 16. Qf1 Nd5 17.
Rf2 $36 {White has excellent attacking prospects on the kingside, whereas
Black's counter-attacking chances are limited.} *

