{In the line starts with 7.b3 Be7 we reach the following opening tabya.
White's last move was 10.Rc1. It is important to understand what White wants
to do in this variation. 1. One of the most common plans is: Ne4-c5 putting
some pressure on the queenside. 2. The other idea is d2-d4 3.White plays Qc2
followed by Rd1 and d4 Black has several alternatives and we can see how White
can employ those plans.} 10... Bg4 {The main move for Black. 11.d4 is not
possible now, but White employs another plan.} (10... Bf5 {The same as 10.. .
a5. Not challenging the centre and White can immediately strike.} 11. d4 $1 {
with similar ideas as in 10...a5.}) (10... Be6 {11.d4 is possible here too,
but I like another plan.} 11. Qc2 $1 {with the idea Rd1,Ne4,d4, etc..}) (10...
a5 {is too slow and not challenging the centre. White should simply continue}
11. d4 $1 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Nb5 c5 14. a4 $1 {At first sight it seems
that Black is just a "healthy" pawn up, but when I analyzed the position
deeper I found that it is really hard for Black to keep his queenside. White's
pieces are much better coordinated and the immediate threat is Ba3. White can
also open the position in his favour through e2-e3 in some cases. The position
is indeed quite promising for White.}) 11. Ne4 {followed by Nc5 and an active
play on the queenside.} *

