1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O Nb6 7. b3 Be7 {
This is Black's first choice in practice.} 8. Bb2 f6 ({The other way of
covering the pawn e5 is too artificial:} 8... Bf6 $6 9. Nc3 Bf5 ({Hardly
better is} 9... e4 10. Ne1 Bf5 11. d3 exd3 12. e4 Bg6 13. Nxd3 O-O 14. Nf4 $36
{Danielsen, H - Romanishin, O Helsingor 2011}) 10. d3 O-O 11. Rc1 Qd7 12. Ne4
Bxe4 13. dxe4 Rfd8 14. Qxd7 Rxd7 15. h4 $16 {The poor location of the Bf6 and
the pressure along the c-file make Black's position very unpleasant. Bakalchuk,
J - Drozdowski, K Dallas 2018}) 9. Nc3 {I like this flexible developing move.
White's knight can be transferred to c5, while d2-d4 might follow in various
cases.} ({The original} 9. Na3 $5 {was recently successfully employed by Top
GM Fabiano Caruana.} Be6 10. Nc2 O-O ({Ineffective is} 10... Qd7 11. e4 O-O-O
12. d4 $36) 11. e4 {This is the point. Now d2-d4 is hard to prevent.} Qd3 (
11... Bg4 12. d4 exd4 13. Ncxd4 Nxd4 14. Qxd4 $14 {is problematic in view of
the poor Nb6.}) 12. Re1 Rad8 ({Undoubtedly, Black has to play} 12... Bg4 $1 13.
Ne3 ({Too passive is} 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Bxf3 Rad8 15. Bc3 Bc5 {, and Black has
excellent piece play.}) 13... Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Qxd2 15. Re2 Qd7 16. Rd1 Nd4 17.
Bxd4 exd4 18. a4 a5 {The control over the light squares offers White decent
compensation for the pawn. Still, Black's position is very solid, so he should
hardly face serious problems here.}) 13. Bf1 Qd7 14. d4 exd4 15. Ncxd4 Bg4 16.
Qc2 Nxd4 17. Nxd4 {White got a long-lasting positional advantage in Caruana, F
- Sevian, S Douglas 2019.}) ({The more forcing} 9. d4 e4 10. Ne1 f5 11. f3 exf3
12. Nxf3 Nd5 13. Qd3 O-O 14. e3 Be6 {led to double-edged play in Nakamura, H -
Hammer, J Stavanger 2015.}) 9... O-O 10. Rc1 {The most common and natural
continuation.} ({Another interesting idea was demonstrated in the following
game:} 10. Qc1 $5 f5 ({After} 10... Be6 11. Rd1 Nd4 (11... Qc8 12. d4 exd4 13.
Nb5 a6 14. Nbxd4 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Bd7 16. e4 $16 {Labussiere, Y - Ramos, A Sao
Paulo 2019}) 12. e3 Nxf3+ 13. Bxf3 c6 14. d4 exd4 15. Ne2 $36 {White seizes
the initiative due to the opposition of the Rd1 and Black's queen.}) 11. Rd1
Be6 ({Worthy of attention is} 11... Bf6 $5 12. d3 Be6) 12. d3 a5 $6 {A
somewhat careless move.} 13. Qe3 $1 Bf6 $2 ({More to the point was} 13... Qd6
14. Nb5 Nd5 15. Qc1 Qd7 16. Na3 $36 {, though even then the e5-pawn is very
weak.}) 14. Nxe5 Bxe5 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Qxe5 {Black was already lost in
Shankland, S - Burg, T Budva 2019}) 10... Bg4 ({After} 10... Be6 {Now I like}
11. Qc2 {, vacating d1 for the king's rook.} ({Starting with} 11. Ne4 Bd5 12.
Qc2 {makes it possible for Black to change the character of play with} Nb4 $5
13. Qb1 Nxa2 14. Nxf6+ Bxf6 15. Qxa2 e4 {The unbalanced position that arose in
Topalov, V - Giri, A Stavanger 2016 looks unclear.}) 11... Qd7 ({After} 11...
Qc8 12. Rfd1 Rd8 13. Ne4 Nd5 14. a3 a5 15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. Qxc5 Nde7 17. Qc2 {
Black was doomed to passive defence in Krush, I - Maack, K Reykjavik 2013}) ({
I've also examined} 11... f5 12. d3 Nd4 ({After} 12... Bf6 13. Na4 $1 Nxa4 14.
bxa4 Qd7 15. Nd2 Bd5 16. Bxd5+ Qxd5 17. Qb3 $14 {The pressure on the c7-pawn
is getting stronger.}) 13. Qb1 Nxf3+ {, and now the unexpected} 14. exf3 $1 {
makes the following d3-d4 break very effective. For instance,} Bf6 15. Rfd1 c6
16. d4 exd4 17. Ne2 $36) 12. Ne4 $146 {Surprisingly, this position was never
met in practice.} ({One preceding game saw} 12. Rfd1 {, but then Black can
solve all the problems at once with} Nb4 $1 13. Qb1 c5) 12... Rad8 ({The
exchange of bishops doesn't solve all Black's problems:} 12... Bh3 13. d4 Bxg2
14. Kxg2 exd4 15. Rfd1 Qe6 16. Bxd4 $14) 13. Rfd1 Qc8 14. d4 f5 15. Nc5 e4 {
Black managed to temporarily neutralize the strong Bg2, but at the permanent
cost of his own bishop.} 16. Nxe6 Qxe6 17. Ne5 Nxe5 18. dxe5 Nd5 19. e3 c6 20.
Bf1 $14 {The powerful bishops offer White long-lasting pressure.}) ({Premature
is} 10... a5 11. d4 $1 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 {This was Iturrizaga Bonelli, E -
Szczepkowska, K Salamanca 2019. Now White could have exploited the drawbacks
of his opponent's setup with} 13. Nb5 $1 $146 c5 14. a4 $1 {The lack of
development starts to tell now:} Be6 ({Worse is} 14... Rb8 $6 15. Qd3 Be6 16.
e3 $16) 15. Ba3 Nd7 16. Re1 Re8 17. Bxb7 Rb8 18. Bg2 $14) ({The somewhat
artificial} 10... Bf5 {traditonally runs into} 11. d4 $1 Nxd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 13.
Nb5 c5 14. b4 {, inviting favorable complications. For instance,} Qd7 15. a4 c4
16. Bxd4 Rfd8 17. Bc5 Qc8 18. Bxe7 Rxd1 19. Rfxd1 $36 {White's initiative more
than compensates for the slight material deficit. Kerr, S - Ivanov, A email
2008}) 11. Ne4 Qc8 {Avoiding the annoying opposition of the Qd8 and White's
rook is a vital measure.} (11... a5 {is again well met by} 12. d4 $1 Bxf3 13.
Bxf3 $146 ({Instead,} 13. exf3 exd4 14. f4 a4 15. Nc5 Bxc5 16. Rxc5 a3 {
wasn't so clear in Garnica,H - Mayer,R (email 2014}) 13... Nxd4 14. Bxd4 exd4
15. Qc2 c6 16. Rcd1 $14 {, followed by e2-e3. White regains the pawn under
favourable circumstances, as the Nb6 is poorly placed.}) 12. Nc5 Bxc5 {
Liquidating the strong Nc5 is the most natural reaction.} (12... Nd7 $6 {
This attempt to get rid of the nasty Nc5 without giving up the bishop fails to}
13. Nxb7 Qxb7 14. Qc2 Nc5 15. Ba3 Nxb3 16. Rb1 Bxa3 17. Qc4+ Kh8 18. Qxg4 $16 {
White regains the piece under favourable circumstances as Black's pawn
structure is damaged.}) (12... Rd8 {was played in two correspondence games.
Now my new natural idea is} 13. b4 $5 $146 Bxc5 (13... Kh8 14. a3 Bxc5 15. Rxc5
e4 16. Nh4 Re8 17. f3 exf3 18. Nxf3 $14) 14. Rxc5 {This looks very promising
for White, whereas the natural attempt to change the route of play with} e4 $6
15. Nh4 Qe6 {is met by} (15... Nd4 16. Bxd4 Rxd4 17. Qc2 $16) 16. h3 $1 Bxh3
17. Bxh3 Qxh3 18. Qb3+ Kf8 (18... Kh8 19. Rh5 $18) 19. b5 Nd4 20. Bxd4 Rxd4 21.
Rxc7 $16) 13. Rxc5 Bh3 ({The pseudo-aggressive} 13... e4 14. Nd4 Nxd4 15. Bxd4
Re8 16. Re1 $14 {leaves the e4-pawn vulnerable.}) 14. b4 {The standard
expansion on the queenside vacates b3 for White's queen.} Rf7 ({After} 14...
Bxg2 15. Qb3+ $1 Kh8 16. Kxg2 $14 {, followed by 17.Rfc1, Black's position
looks too passive.}) 15. Bxh3 (15. b5 Nd8 16. d4 Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Ne6 18. Rc1 e4
19. Nd2 Qd7 20. Nxe4 Qd5 21. f3 Qxb5 22. Qb3 Qxb3 23. axb3 Nd5 24. Kf2 f5 25.
Nc3 {1/2 (25) Petrovic,D (2351) -Ritter,K (2257) Remote email 2013}) 15... Qxh3
16. Qb3 a5 {We have been following the correspondence game Vaillant, F -
Duchardt,A email 2015 Now most challenging seems} 17. b5 $146 Nd8 18. Rxc7 a4
19. Qc2 Rxc7 20. Qxc7 Qe6 {The a2-pawn is hanging, so White's queen
temporarily has to go back.} 21. Qc5 Rc8 22. Qa3 Qd5 {Now the b5-pawn should
fall, so White has to play energetically:} 23. Rc1 Qxb5 24. d4 $1 exd4 (24...
e4 {drops the pawn:} 25. Qe7 $1 exf3 26. Rxc8 Nxc8 27. Qxd8+ Kf7 28. Qxc8 Qxb2
29. Qc4+ Kg6 30. exf3) 25. Nxd4 Rxc1+ 26. Bxc1 $14 *

