1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Nf3 Nc6 6. O-O Nb6 7. b3 g6 {
This move is employed by many grandmasters. Naturally, Black wants to
neutralize the pressure along the a1-h8 diagonal.} 8. Nc3 {A flexible move.
White reasonably assumes that Black's bishop will be developed to g7 in any
case, so his dark-squared bishop may be located well on a3.} Bg7 ({The waiting
} 8... a5 {can be energetically met by} 9. d4 $1 exd4 ({Equally good for White
is} 9... Nxd4 10. Nxe5 Bg7 11. f4 O-O 12. Be3 c5 13. Rc1 $36 {Becelic, D -
Nestorovic, D Belgrade 2017}) 10. Nb5 Bg7 11. Bg5 Qd7 12. Rc1 O-O 13. Qd2 a4
14. Rfd1 axb3 15. axb3 $14 {White regains the pawn under favourable
circumstances, as Black's development isn't yet completed.}) 9. Ba3 a5 {
Black intends to lock the key diagonal a3-f8.} ({Too passive is} 9... Ne7 10.
Rc1 O-O 11. d4 exd4 12. Nb5 Nbd5 13. Nbxd4 $14 {Svane,R - Bulski,K Germany 2014
}) 10. d3 Nb4 11. Nd2 {The knight is heading to c4 to pose Black some concrete
problems.} O-O 12. Nc4 Nxc4 (12... e4 $5 $146 {looks scary, but after} 13. Nxe4
f5 14. Nc5 Bxa1 15. Qxa1 Nc2 {Black manages to exchange the strong
dark-squared bishop. Still, after} 16. Qb2 Nxa3 17. Qxa3 Nxc4 18. bxc4 {
White has promising play for the exchange.}) 13. bxc4 c6 ({Worse is} 13... e4
$2 14. Nxe4 Bxa1 15. Qxa1 Nc2 16. Nf6+ Kh8 {Black's king was very exposed in
Cyborowski,L - Licznerski,L Police 2019 , and now} 17. Qc1 $1 Nxa3 18. Qh6 {
would have won on spot.}) 14. Qb3 Qe7 15. Rab1 $14 {Black's position was shaky
in Harutyunian, T - Suarez Uriel, A Roquetas de Mar 2020.} *

