1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Bc5 4. Nc3 O-O 5. Nf3 Nc6 ({I was surprised to
discover that this bad move was made by a few very strong players. Until now
the clear refutation wasn't demonstrated:} 5... Re8 $2 6. Nxe5 $1 $146 {
Amazingly, this typical idea is new in this position!} Bxf2+ (6... Rxe5 7. d4
Bxd4 8. Qxd4 d6 9. O-O Nc6 10. Qd2 {is close to winning for White from a
positional point of view: He has both the better pawn structure and the strong
unopposed dark-squared bishop.}) 7. Kxf2 Rxe5 8. d4 Re8 9. Rf1 d6 10. Kg1 $16 {
It would be very hard for Black to withstand the storm of White's central
pawns that are supported by powerful bishops.}) ({Allowing d2-d4 with} 5... d6
{is a certain positional concession:} 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 Re8 8. O-O Nbd7 9. b3
a6 10. Bb2 {Black got under long-lasting pressure in Adams, M - Gormally, D
Bournemouth 2016.}) (5... e4 6. Ng5 Bxf2+ 7. Kxf2 Ng4+ 8. Kg1 Qxg5 9. Bxe4 Qf6
10. Qf1 Qb6+ 11. Kg2 Nf6 12. Bf3 d6 13. d3 h6 14. h3 Nc6 15. Qf2 {White's
advantage was undeniable due to his bishop pair in Slawinski, T - Jankowiak, A
email 2010.}) 6. O-O d6 7. e3 {The d2-d4 advance looks especially appealing
when Black's bishop is on c5.} Bg4 {By pinning the Nf3 Black is trying to
provoke a weakening of White's pawn chain.} ({The prophylactic} 7... a6 8. d4
Ba7 {seems somewhat slow, but White has to play precisely to prove its
drawbacks:} 9. h3 $1 {It's vital to avoid the pin on g4.} h6 10. b3 Bf5 (10...
Re8 {leads to approximately the same character of play:} 11. dxe5 dxe5 12. Bb2
Bf5 13. Nd5 Be4 14. Nh4 Bxg2 15. Kxg2 $14 {Vachier Lagrave,M - Balogh,C Saint
Louis 2012}) ({Insufficient is also} 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. exd4 Re8 13.
Qd3 Rb8 14. a4 Be6 {Natural play by both sides led to this position in Sarno,
S - Arlandi, E Reggio Emilia 1997. Now the simple} 15. Bf4 $146 d5 16. c5 {
would have put Black in a passive position.}) 11. dxe5 $1 {This is the most
energetic way of handling the position - all White's minor pieces are getting
activated.} dxe5 12. Ba3 {White gains an important tempo!} Re8 13. Qxd8 Raxd8
14. Rfd1 e4 {Miezis, N -Tregubov, P Flims 2016 At this point White could have
exploited the weakness of the e4-pawn by} 15. Nh4 $1 $146 Bc8 (15... Bh7 16. g4
$16) 16. g4 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 g6 18. Rd2 $14) ({Black can hardly achieve an
attractive position either with} 7... Bf5 8. d4 Bb6 9. a3 a5 {This was Snape,
I - Martin,A West Bromwich 2004. Now the simple} 10. h3 Re8 11. b3 h6 12. Bb2
$14 {would have put Black in a passive position due to the poor Bb6.}) (7...
Bb6 8. d4 Re8 (8... Bg4 {has no independent value:} 9. h3 Bh5 ({After} 9...
Bxf3 10. Bxf3 exd4 11. exd4 {the powerful bishops offer White a clear
positional advantage.}) 10. g4 Bg6 {transposes to the mainline.}) (8... Bf5 {
is also a transposition.}) 9. h3 h6 {This was seen in a couple of games. For
some reason, the following natural way of handling the position is completely
new:} ({In case of} 9... Bf5 {White can slowly prepare his intentions on the
queenside with} 10. a3 a5 11. b3 Qd7 12. Kh2 h6 {This position occurred in
Schandorff,L - Hansen,C Vejstrup 1989. At this moment White shouldn't deviate
from the most natural} 13. Bb2 exd4 14. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 15. cxd5 Ne5 16. Nxd4 Bd3
17. Re1 $14 {This pawn structure traditionally favours White, who has a
serious space advantage.}) 10. dxe5 $5 $146 dxe5 ({After} 10... Nxe5 11. b3 Bf5
12. Nxe5 dxe5 13. Bxb7 Bxh3 14. Qxd8 Raxd8 15. Rd1 $14 {White has the better
pawn structure.}) 11. Qxd8 Rxd8 12. b3 Be6 13. Bb2 Nd7 ({After} 13... e4 14.
Nh2 Bf5 15. Rfd1 $14 {Black has no compensation for the weak pawn on e4.}) 14.
Rfd1 f6 15. Nd5 $14 {White has a slight but long-lasting positional advantage.}
) (7... Re8 {Too artificial is} 8. d4 Bb4 {Kabanov,N - Golovin,L Voronezh 2006
White can now exploit the lack of harmony in Black's camp by playing} (8... Bb6
{transposes to 7...Bb6.}) 9. Nd5 $1 e4 10. Nd2 Nxd5 11. cxd5 Bxd2 12. Bxd2 Nb8
13. f3 $36) 8. h3 Bh5 9. g4 $1 {White isn't afraid of ghosts!} Bg6 10. d4 Bb6 (
{Much worse is} 10... exd4 $6 11. exd4 Bb6 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Nb8 14. Nd5 Nbd7
15. Re1 $16 {Nilsen,J - Akobian,V chess.com 2017}) 11. dxe5 $1 {This makes the
e5-pawn temporarily vulnerable.} (11. Nh4 $5 Nd7 $2 (11... exd4 $1 12. exd4
Nxd4 13. Nxg6 hxg6 14. Bxb7 $13) 12. Nxg6 hxg6 13. dxe5 $16 {1-0 (37) Schmitz,
T (2302)-Veys,V (2167) Boeblingen 2013}) 11... dxe5 12. b4 $1 e4 ({In case of} 
12... Nxb4 13. Nxe5 Qe7 14. Nxg6 hxg6 {Kleinsorgen,H - Brousek,J email 2004
White should play} 15. Rb1 $1 c6 16. g5 Nh7 17. Ne4 $16 {, obtaining a big
positional advantage due to his bishop pair and the pressure along the b-file.}
) 13. Nh4 Nxb4 14. Nxg6 hxg6 15. g5 Nd7 16. Nxe4 Nc5 {This position occurred
in Fressinet, L - Karpov, A Cap d'Agde 2015 Now my suggestion is:} 17. Qxd8
$146 Raxd8 18. Rb1 Nxe4 19. Bxe4 Nxa2 20. Bxb7 Nxc1 21. Rfxc1 $14 {Despite the
bishops of different colour, achieving a draw is a tough task for Black.} *

