{[%evp 0,2,11,15,11]} {An important position. White's knight on h4 is in
danger, but it is not so easy for Black to use this. On the other hand, White
starts undermining Black's centre. Black can't keep his central pawns and need
to seek some active counterplay. There are three main replies:} 8... Ng4 {
The most ambitious move and the main line. Black puts pressure on f2 and wants
to trap the knight by 9...g5} (8... Bb4 {is well met by} 9. dxe4 {and then
both 9...d4 and 9...dxe4 failed to equalize}) (8... exd3 {leads to an
unpleasant endgame for Black after:} 9. Qxd3 d4 10. Ne4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4+ Qe7 12.
Qxe7+ Kxe7 {White has a small but stable advantage in this endgame.}) 9. O-O {
This position was tried in some high-level games. I think that White keeps
better chances after both 9...g5 or 9...e3} *

