1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 Bc5 4. Nc3 c6 {This way of handling the position has
been known for more than a century, but it only gained popularity in recent
years. Like in most cases where Black plays c7-c6, his main idea is to build
up a strong pawn centre and restrict White's light-squared bishop. There are
also undeniable merits of placing the bishop on c5: White cannot go for an
early d2-d4 or place his knight on d4 (like it often happens after 2...c6 or 3.
..c6).} 5. Nf3 ({The most common alternative is} 5. e3 d5 6. cxd5 {, but after}
O-O $1 ({worse is} 6... Nxd5 7. Nf3 Bg4 8. Qa4 $14) 7. Nge2 Nxd5 8. d4 exd4 9.
Nxd5 cxd5 10. Nxd4 (10. exd4 Bb6 11. O-O Nc6 {was proven to be safe for Black.}
) 10... Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. O-O Be6 13. Qc2 Qb6 14. b3 d4 $11 {White's
superior pawn structure only had a symbolic value in Carlsen, M - Ding Liren
Stavanger NOR 2018}) 5... e4 {The only challenging reply.} ({Too passive is} 
5... d6 6. d4 exd4 7. Nxd4 O-O 8. O-O Re8 9. Bf4 {Black had no compensation
for his structural drawbacks in Saric, A - Kurajica, B Zadar 2008}) 6. Nh4 {
Obviously the Nh4 is in danger. However, Black has to expose his king to trap
it.} d5 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. d3 Ng4 {This aggressive continuation is the only way
to exploit the awkward location of the Nh4.} ({The endgame that might arises
after} 8... exd3 9. Qxd3 d4 10. Ne4 Nxe4 11. Qxe4+ Qe7 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 13. O-O
Nc6 14. Bd2 $14 {offers White a stable positional advantage due to the
powerful Bg2.}) ({Dubious is} 8... Bb4 $6 9. dxe4 Nxe4 ({After} 9... d4 10. O-O
dxc3 11. Qa4+ Nc6 12. e5 $16 {White regains the piece and maintains all the
merits of his position.}) 10. O-O Bxc3 (10... Nxc3 11. bxc3 Bxc3 12. Rb1 Nc6
13. Bxd5 $16) 11. bxc3 O-O 12. c4 Nc3 13. Qd2 d4 {This was Heberla, B -
Artemiev, V Kocaeli 2014 Now strongest was} 14. e3 $1 $146 Re8 15. Bb2 Nc6 16.
Rfe1 Bg4 17. h3 Bh5 18. exd4 Ne2+ 19. Kh2 Ncxd4 20. Rad1 $18 {Black cannot
avoid major loss of material.}) 9. O-O ({After} 9. dxe4 Bxf2+ ({but not} 9...
Nxf2 $2 10. Qxd5 Qxd5 11. Nxd5 Nxh1 12. Nc7+ Kd8 13. Nxa8 Nf2 14. Bf4 $18) 10.
Kf1 d4 11. Nd5 O-O 12. Bf3 Be3 {Black doesn't experience any problems.}) 9...
g5 ({The alternative} 9... e3 10. fxe3 Bxe3+ 11. Kh1 {looks shaky, since
Black's development is too delayed. For instance,} d4 12. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 13. Qb3
O-O 14. Qxb7 dxc3 15. Qxa8 $16) 10. d4 {White temporarily locks the central
files, but Black's bishop is forced to leave his active position.} ({Deserving
of attention is also} 10. dxe4 $5 gxh4 11. Qxd5 $1 $146 ({At the same time,} 
11. exd5 $2 hxg3 12. hxg3 {Khismatullin,D - Paravyan,D St Petersburg 2016} Nd7
13. Ne4 Bb6 $17 {doesn't offer White much for the piece.}) 11... Na6 12. Qxd8+
Kxd8 13. Bg5+ Be7 14. Rad1+ Bd7 15. Bf4 $44 {Even though the queens are off
the board, White still retains promising compensation for the piece. Black's
pieces have no good coordination, while the king is unsafe.}) 10... Be7 (10...
Bb6 11. Nf3 $1 exf3 ({After} 11... h6 12. Ne5 Nxe5 13. dxe5 Be6 14. Kh1 Nc6 15.
f4 Qd7 16. f5 Bxf5 17. Nxd5 {The knight reaches f6, so White has a promising
position.}) 12. exf3 Nf6 (12... Nh6 13. Re1+ Kf8 14. Re5 f6 15. Rxd5 $16) 13.
Bxg5 h6 14. Bh4 O-O 15. f4 $36 {The nasty pin and the weak pawn on d5 make
Black's position dangerous, even though there are only two pawns for the piece
at the moment.}) 11. h3 gxh4 $146 {Black reasonably takes the knight
immediately, since now White's king is getting more exposed.} ({Worse is} 11...
Nxf2 $6 12. Rxf2 gxh4 13. Qb3 $1 hxg3 14. Rf4 {Black is two pawns up now, but
the lack of development makes it impossible to retain the material advantage.}
Nc6 15. Qxd5 f5 16. Bxe4 $1 {A stunning piece sacrifice.} fxe4 $2 ({Better was
} 16... Qxd5 17. Bxd5 Bd7 18. Be3 h5 19. h4 O-O-O 20. Rc1 $16 {, but even then
Black has a difficult endgame: White's pieces are very active, while the
g3-pawn may fall soon.}) 17. Qh5+ Kd7 18. Be3 Qg8 19. d5 $18 {Black was soon
crushed in Anton Guijarro, D - Grischuk, A Douglas 2019}) 12. hxg4 hxg3 ({
Another natural continuation is} 12... Nc6 13. f3 exf3 14. Bxf3 Be6 15. Bf4
hxg3 (15... Qd7 16. e4 $1 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Bxg4 18. Qd2 Nxd4 19. Rae1 O-O-O 20.
Qc1 $36 {Black's king is in big danger, so his extra pawns are not the main
factor.}) 16. Kg2 $1 {A nice cool-blooded move, which enables White to employ
his rook.} Qd7 17. Rh1 O-O-O (17... Bxg4 18. e3 $1 Bxf3+ 19. Qxf3 O-O-O 20. Rh5
f5 21. Rc1 $16) 18. Rc1 Bxg4 19. Rh6 Bxf3+ 20. exf3 $36 {The activity of his
pieces offers White more than sufficient compensation for the pawns.}) 13. f3
Nc6 14. fxe4 dxe4 15. Be3 {This developing move looks most appealing.} ({
In case of} 15. e3 $5 {Black should act very creatively to maintain his
counterplay:} Bb4 $1 16. Nxe4 Qh4 17. Rf4 h5 $1 18. Qb3 Be6 19. d5 O-O-O 20.
dxe6 fxe6 $44) 15... Bg5 16. Qd2 Bxe3+ 17. Qxe3 Qxd4 {Black should be happy
with liquidating into an endgame in such a position.} 18. Qxd4 Nxd4 19. Rad1
Nc6 20. Nxe4 $14 {White will manage to regain the pawn under favourable
circumstances.} *

