{[%evp 0,4,-51,-2,-50,13,-120]} {This is the starting position of the
following chapter. The position resembles Alapin Variation in Sicilian Defence
with reversed colors. White's main plan is to put some pressure in the centre
employing Nc3 and d3 (sometimes even f3) Black has four possible plans. I will
explain in a few words how we need to react against all of them.} 7... Qe5 {
The strongest move. Here the reader should remember the following idea.} (7...
Bc5 {Is the most popular move, but it runs to 8.d3! and White is better.}) (
7... Bg4 {Is insufficient for equality due to:} 8. Nc3 $1 Bxd1 9. Nxd5 cxd5 10.
Kxd1 $14 {All those endgames where White ends up with a bishop pair are better
for us.}) (7... Na6 {Looks strange and should be met by} 8. d3 $1) 8. d3 $1
exd3 9. Nd2 $1 {White is exploiting his lead in development. We will take the
pawn on d3 later.} *

