1. c4 e5 2. g3 Nf6 3. Bg2 c6 4. Nf3 e4 5. Nd4 d5 6. cxd5 Qxd5 {A double-edged
decision. Black recaptures the pawn with a tempo, after which any retreat of
White's knight would be a concession. On the flipside, the Qd5 is clearly
misplaced, so Black will have to spend another tempo to move it again.} 7. e3
Qe5 {The most solid choice. Black moves his queen in advance and invites White
to show his cards.} ({Insufficient for equality is} 7... Bg4 8. Nc3 Bxd1 9.
Nxd5 cxd5 10. Kxd1 Bc5 $6 ({Better was} 10... Nc6 11. Nxc6 bxc6 12. Ke2 Bd6 13.
d3 exd3+ 14. Kxd3 Ke7 15. b3 $14) 11. Nb5 Kd7 12. b3 a6 13. Nc3 Nc6 14. Bb2 {
White's advantage was undeniable in Vo,T - Tran,M Vietnam 2016}) ({Another
natural continuation is} 7... Bc5 {, but this is well met by} 8. d3 $1 Bxd4 ({
Hardly better is} 8... Qe5 9. dxe4 Nxe4 10. Nc3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 O-O 12. O-O Rd8 {
This was Shimanov,A - Triapishko,O Sochi 2017 At this moment White should have
played} 13. a4 $1 $146 a5 (13... Bf8 14. Qb3 Na6 15. e4 Nc5 16. Qc2 $14) 14.
Qe2 Nd7 15. e4 Qe7 16. h3 $14 {[%csl Rc8][%cal Gf2f4,Ge4e5] White has great
prospects on the kingside, while Black's position looks rather passive.}) 9.
exd4 Qxd4 10. dxe4 {White manages to liquidate into a favorable endgame in
which he has the bishop pair.} Qxd1+ 11. Kxd1 O-O 12. f3 c5 {This position
occured in Dubov, D - Bologan, V Poikovsky 2017 At this point there was no
reason for rejecting the most natural} 13. Nc3 $146 Nc6 14. Ke2 Be6 15. Be3 b6
16. Rhd1 Rfd8 17. Kf2 $14) ({Too artificial is} 7... Na6 8. d3 Bb4+ 9. Nc3 Nc5
10. O-O Bxc3 {This is a certain concession, but the Bb4 was rather useless
anyway.} 11. dxe4 Ncxe4 12. bxc3 O-O 13. Qc2 c5 {This posiiton took place in
Gelfand, B - Inarkiev, E Nazran 2017 Now White should have played} 14. c4 $1
$146 Qe5 15. Nb3 Bf5 16. Bb2 Qe6 17. Qe2 Bg6 18. f3 Nd6 19. Rac1 {White's pawn
majority on the k-side is supported by powerful bishops, so Black's position
is unpleasant.}) 8. d3 $1 {It's important to immediately challenge Black's
centre and activate the light-squared bishop.} ({Less precise is} 8. Nc3 Bb4 9.
Qc2 Bxc3 10. Qxc3 O-O 11. b3 {Kolbus,D - Chudinovskikh,A Marianske Lazne 2019
in view of} Re8 $1 12. O-O (12. Bb2 Nd5 13. Qc4 b6 $15) 12... c5 13. Nb5 Qe7
14. Bb2 a6 15. Na3 b5 {The poor location of the queen's knight causes White
certain problems.}) 8... exd3 ({I've also examined} 8... c5 9. Ne2 exd3 10.
Qxd3 Nc6 11. O-O Be7 12. Qc3 O-O 13. b3 Rd8 14. Bb2 Qxc3 15. Nbxc3 $14 {
White has a slight but long-lasting positional advantage due to his strong Bg2.
}) 9. Nd2 $1 {Only this makes it possible for White to exploit the awkward
location of his opponent's centralized queen.} ({Not much is offered by} 9.
Qxd3 Bc5 10. O-O O-O 11. Nc3 Rd8 12. Qc2 Na6 $11 {Zwardon, V - Dhulipalla, B
Pardubice 2018.}) 9... Bc5 ({The timid} 9... Be7 10. Nc4 Qc7 11. Qxd3 O-O 12.
O-O $14 {leaves Black in a passive position.}) 10. Nc4 Qh5 {Black invites
favourable simplifications, but his knight will be out of play for a while.} ({
The alternative is} 10... Qe7 11. Qxd3 O-O 12. O-O Rd8 13. b3 $1 Bxd4 (13...
Na6 14. Bb2 Nb4 15. Qb1 $14) 14. exd4 Be6 15. Ba3 Qc7 16. Rfe1 Na6 17. Re2 $14
{[%cal Ge6d5,Ge2e7]} Bd5 18. Re7 Rd7 19. Rae1 {[%csl Ra6]}) 11. Qxh5 Nxh5 {
We have been following the game Shankland,S - Xiong,J Saint Louis USA 2019.
Now my natural improvement over Sam's play is} 12. O-O O-O 13. Rd1 Bxd4 (13...
Na6 {is well met by} 14. Nb3 $1 Be7 15. Rxd3 $14 {White regains the pawn in a
favourable situation.}) 14. exd4 Na6 ({The attempt to fix his control of d5 by
means of} 14... Nf6 15. Rxd3 Na6 {fails to} 16. Bg5 Nb4 17. Rb3 $1 Nfd5 18. Nd6
$36) ({Even worse is} 14... Be6 $6 15. Na5 $16) 15. Bg5 h6 16. Be7 Re8 17. Ba3
Bg4 18. Rxd3 Be2 19. Rc3 $14 {The lack of harmony in Black's camp makes his
position rather uncomfortable.} *

