1. c4 e5 2. g3 c6 {This is one of the most ambitious responses. Black uses the
fact that none of White's knights is developed yet, so it is easier to expand
in the centre.} 3. Nf3 ({Another common move is} 3. d4 {, but the position,
that arises after} e4 4. Nc3 d5 5. Bg2 Nf6 6. Bg5 Nbd7 {proved to be
comfortable for the second player.}) 3... e4 4. Nd4 {This is almost a reversed
Alapin, but the extra g2-g3 clearly favours White.} d5 (4... Nf6 5. Bg2 {
is covered in a separate chapter.}) 5. cxd5 Qxd5 ({The other natural recapture
} 5... cxd5 $6 {makes Black's central pawns too exposed.} 6. d3 Nf6 7. Bg2 Bc5
(7... Bb4+ 8. Nc3 O-O 9. O-O Bxc3 10. bxc3 Re8 11. Bf4 a6 {was seen in
Szekeres, T - Szakolczai,P Hungary 1994. At this point White should have played
} 12. c4 $1 dxc4 13. dxc4 Qa5 14. h3 {White's bishop pair and the weak e4-pawn
make Black's position unpleasant.}) 8. Nb3 Bb6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3 e3 (10... Bf5
$2 11. Bg5 {led to the loss of a central pawn in Mamedyarov, S - Ganguly, S
Kolkata 2018}) 11. fxe3 Re8 {This was Stamenkov, V - Mastrovasilis, D
Kalamaria 2006 Now the thematic sacrifice} 12. Rxf6 $1 Qxf6 13. Nxd5 Qd6 14.
Nd2 Be6 15. Nc4 Qd8 16. Ncxb6 axb6 17. e4 $16 {would have offered White full
control over the centre.}) 6. Nc2 $1 {This retreat is the most effective - the
knight can be well placed on e3.} ({After} 6. Nb3 Nf6 7. Nc3 Qh5 8. Bg2 Bh3 $1
$132 {Black has excellent prospects on the kingside.}) 6... Nf6 ({Dubious is} 
6... e3 $6 7. f3 exd2+ 8. Bxd2 Nf6 9. e4 Qd8 10. Nc3 Bc5 11. Qe2 O-O 12. O-O-O
Be6 13. g4 $36 {White's setup is perfect for aggressive measures on the
kingside.}) 7. Nc3 Qe5 ({Another standard retreat,} 7... Qh5 {, is usually
connected with the promising idea of exchanging the light-squared bishops.
Therefore, White should continue:} 8. Ne3 $1 Bc5 (8... Bh3 $6 {is met by} 9.
Qb3 $1 b6 10. Qa4 {, and Black's position is shaky.}) 9. Qc2 Qe5 (9... Bxe3 10.
fxe3 Bf5 (10... Qe5 {doesn't have an independent value, since} 11. Bg2 Bf5 {
leads to the text.}) 11. Bg2 Qg6 {was tried in Navara, D - Nisipeanu, L
Reykjavik 2015 At this point White shouldn't deviate from the natural} 12. O-O
O-O 13. b4 Nbd7 14. Bb2 Rfe8 15. Rf4 {The powerful bishop pair and the
activity along the f-file offer White a promising initiative. For instance,}
Nd5 16. Rxf5 $1 Qxf5 17. Bxe4 Qh5 18. Nxd5 cxd5 19. Bf3 Qg5 20. Qc7 {White's
superiority is undeniable.}) 10. Bg2 Bxe3 11. fxe3 Bf5 12. b4 $1 {A
multi-purpose move: White starts the so-called minority attack and also
activates his dark-squared bishop.} O-O 13. Bb2 Nbd7 ({Deserving of attention
is} 13... Qe6 $5 {, but the unbalanced position that arises after} 14. g4 $1
Nxg4 15. Nxe4 Qh6 16. h4 Nd7 17. Qc3 {looks very promising for White, whose
unopposed dark-squared bishop is a monster.}) 14. O-O Qe6 15. b5 Bg6 16. Qb3
Nd5 17. Rac1 {White was better in Aronian, L - Papaioannou, I Hersonissos 2017}
) 8. Bg2 ({Weaker is} 8. d4 exd3 9. Qxd3 Bf5 10. Qe3 Qxe3 11. Nxe3 Be6 $11 {
Duda,J - Yilmaz,M Gjakova 2016}) 8... Na6 ({After} 8... Be7 9. Ne3 Na6 10. Qc2
Nb4 11. Qb1 Nbd5 12. Nxe4 Nxe3 13. dxe3 {Black didn't have adequate
compensation for the pawn in Navara, D - Balogh, C Achaea 2016}) 9. O-O ({
Less effective is} 9. Ne3 Bc5 $1 10. Qc2 Nb4 11. Qb1 Bxe3 12. fxe3 Bf5 {
Black's chances were not worse to say the least. Puranik, A - Prithu, G Moscow
RUS 2019}) 9... Be7 10. d3 exd3 11. Qxd3 {Visually, this looks fine for Black,
who has no real weaknesses. However, White's setup is more harmonious, so
there are still some problems to solve.} O-O (11... Nc5 {can be well met by}
12. Qe3 $146 (12. Qd4 {, as in Tomashevsky, E - Grischuk, A Moscow 2019 seems
less precise in view of} Qh5 $1 13. Rd1 O-O {, and Black has excellent
counter-attacking prospects on the kingside.}) 12... Qh5 13. Qg5 {Exchanging
the annoying Qh5 is an undeniable achievement for White.} Qxg5 14. Bxg5 h6 15.
Bf4 O-O (15... Bf5 16. Nd4 $14) 16. Rfd1 a5 17. Bd6 Bxd6 18. Rxd6 Re8 19. Rad1
Kf8 20. f3 $14 {White has the upper hand in the centre, while Black's pawns
majority on the queenside doesn't offer him sufficient counterplay.}) 12. Qe3
Bd6 {Black is trying to activate his dark-squared bishop.} ({Hardly stronger is
} 12... Qxe3 13. Bxe3 Nb4 (13... Bf5 14. Nd4 Bg6 15. Nb3 $14) 14. Nxb4 Bxb4 15.
a3 Be7 (15... Bxc3 16. bxc3 Re8) 16. b4 $14) 13. Rd1 Re8 {This was Hammer,J -
Giri,A Moscow 2017 Now my natural new idea is} 14. Qxe5 Bxe5 15. e4 Nc5 16. f3
$14 {Black is doomed to passive defence.} *

